    <title>The first League of Legends indie spinoffs are out now</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/TKW6cQalREmm7sMuXx02gNGAGgk=/150x0:1770x1080/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/70149638/29_Hero_Yasuo.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ruined King.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="MiuKSX"&gt;In late 2019, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/5/20993328/riot-forge-publishing-label-league-of-legends-games"&gt;Riot revealed a new publishing label&lt;/a&gt; designed to give indie studios the chance to play around in the vast &lt;em&gt;League of Legends&lt;/em&gt; universe — and today, the first two Forge games are finally releasing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OISmDl"&gt;That includes &lt;em&gt;Hextech Mayhem&lt;/em&gt;, a rhythm platformer from &lt;em&gt;Bit.Trip&lt;/em&gt; developer Choice Provisions, which is out on the Switch and PC, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/11/9/22772338/league-of-legends-spinoff-netflix-games-nintendo-switch-hextech-mayhem"&gt;with a version also coming to Netflix Games in the future&lt;/a&gt;. Joining it is &lt;em&gt;Ruined King&lt;/em&gt;, a turn-based role-playing game from Airship Syndicate, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/12/21012514/league-of-legends-riot-indie-game-ruined-king-the-game-awards-tga"&gt;which was previously revealed in 2019&lt;/a&gt;. It’s launching first on the PC, Switch, PS4, and Xbox One, with next-gen versions for PlayStation and Xbox also on the way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="n6IhFN"&gt;&lt;div style="left: 0; width: 100%; height: 0; position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id="bddC5N"&gt;&lt;div style="left: 0; width: 100%; height: 0; position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
